                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-06-22</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>An enjoyable and engrossing examination of a unique confluence of time, place, and people ... Eastern European Jewish immigrants, their first-generation-American children, the Great Depression, Brownsville NY, and the crime Syndicate born of Prohibition.  <p>Ron Ross recreates a world of candy stores, pushcart vendors, tenement apartments, petty thugs, corner gyms, notorious gangsters, and the struggle for life and dignity admist poverty, crime, and prejudice.  Vivid, colorful, and often humorous, it's also grim, unblinking, and heart rending.<p>A great book for students of Jewish-American history, for boxing enthusiasts, for organized crime buffs, and for those who simply appreciate a great story.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">devasting story of trying to survive the depression...</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
